  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The memory element learns to capture local information, non-linear interactions, and patterns among tokens that appear at that position.",
    "The underlying syntactic and semantic rules of a language govern the probability that specific words will appear at specific positions, and those statistics are language dependent.",
    "For example, sentences often begin with subjects (I, you, he, she, it, we, they) or proper nouns such the names of people or places (Manning and Schutze 1999).",
    "Intuition: Having independent FFNN at each position enables efficient parallelized operations that can occur independently and simultaneously across multiple independent processors.",
    "The linear network above the decoder stack computes a joint probability distribution over the vocabulary for the contextualized tokens that flow through each position."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "For example, sentences often begin with subjects (I, you, he, she, it, we, they) or proper nouns such the names of people or places (Manning and Schutze 1999)."
  ]
